Well, I hope, we will not wait that all glance py35 tests pass to merge this. Not be able to bump eventlet blocks other projects to merge changes.

Patch Set 1:

We don't need to wait for py35, but there is no reason to intentionally break changes we know are coming down the pipe, since the fix is as simple as selectively patching only the modules that are needed, instead of all of them.

Patch Set 1:

This what glance does in api/scruber/...:

  eventlet.patcher.monkey_patch(all=False, socket=True, time=True,
                                select=True, thread=True, os=True)


If you put a different monkey pacthing in your functional tests, you will not really test the same code path than the real glance software run. Making many assumption wrong.

If test doesn't pass after this change, we have a good chance the tests is doing wrong thing.

Hemanth, I think both api and scrubber now are mokeypatching all the modules. So is the current patch. Cos, all the 5 parameters that eventlet's monkey_patch() takes have been enabled there. [1] I think it is okay to be implicitly state the same here.
Registry on the other hand has enabled only socket, time and thread.

It may be the same. Or not? http://eventlet.net/doc/patching.html#eventlet.patcher.monkey_patch

Looks like now psycopg can be monkey patched as well. Now, we don't use postgres, so it is probably not an issue. But, can you see what I'm concerned about? Monkey patching ``all`` is very implicit. If eventlet adds support for something else tomorrow, then that would get monkey patched by default too irrespective of our intention. We'll then be looking at a nasty debugging scenario.

Call me paranoid but explicit is better than implicit. 
Moreover, what is ``all`` buying us that explicit monkey patching doesn't? Help me understand.

From what I understand, eventlet 0.20.x removed ``poll``. So, if we patch select it's not going to have ``poll``, which is used by subprocess to communicate. Unless we patch  subprocess too, patching select alone will break subprocess usage.

I'm not entirely sure myself but that's what I got so far.

Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

I have my reservations against this one. Patching select without patching subprocess I think is a bomb waiting to go off. I tried looking at all the places where we use subprocess and thus need select.poll. It looks like Glance directly uses this primarily for bringing up servers for functional tests. Apart from that I couldn't find a direct use of it anywhere else. But, I'm not 100% sure that we won't break Glance going forward with direct or indirect usage of subprocess that requires select.poll. 

Keeping the above in mind and given that this is blocking the entire community from moving to eventlet 0.20.x, I'm willing to merge this with reservations.
